====================================================================

ðŸ“„ DESCRIPTION
--------------------------------------------------------------------

LECTURE DEFINITIONS:
  â€¢ Phenomena = observable instances  
        (ex: â€œuser#41 logs in at 12:04 PMâ€)
  â€¢ Concepts = abstract kinds  
        (ex: â€œAdminâ€, â€œPlayerâ€, â€œOrganizerâ€)

PROJECT APPLICATION:
  Concept-Level (Abstract):
      - Role definitions: Admin, Player, Organizer, President
      - Permissions per role
      - Profile structure

  Phenomenon-Level (Concrete):
      - Logged-in user instance
      - Session activity
      - Role changes in runtime

DOMAIN ENTITIES:
  - ROLE
  - PROFILE
  - PERMISSIONS

FUNCTIONS:
  - AssignRole
  - AuthenticateUser
  - ValidatePermission

EVENTS:
  - UserLogin
  - RoleChange
  - SessionTimeout

BEHAVIORS:
  - Admin moderation
  - Player actions
  - Role-based UI rendering

====================================================================

ASCII CONCEPT vs PHENOMENON DIAGRAM
--------------------------------------------------------------------

Concept Layer:
--------------

     +-----------------------+
     |         ROLE          |
     | Admin, Player, etc.   |
     +-----------------------+
                |
     +-----------------------+
     |     PERMISSIONS       |
     +-----------------------+
                |
     +-----------------------+
     |       PROFILE         |
     +-----------------------+

Phenomenon Layer:
-----------------

user#41 ---- logs in as ----> Admin  
user#22 ---- logs in as ----> Player  
user#78 ---- logs in as ----> Organizer  

====================================================================

ASCII EVENT FLOW
--------------------------------------------------------------------

[LOGIN] --> [FETCH ROLE] --> [APPLY PERMISSIONS] --> allowed?

====================================================================

ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA
--------------------------------------------------------------------
- Roles documented as concepts.
- User instances documented as phenomena.
- Distinction reflected in diagrams + functions.
- Lecture-based justification included.

